Step-by-step logic
Pass 1: Reverse only letters

i starts at the left, j at the right

Move i forward until it hits a letter

Move j backward until it hits a letter

Swap them

Continue until i >= j

Special characters are skipped automatically.

Pass 2: Reverse only special characters

Reset i = 0, j = n-1

Move i forward until it hits a special character

Move j backward until it hits a special character

Swap them

Now letters stay fixed, and specials get reversed.


Approach 4: 
Step 1: Collect indices

Walk once through the string.

letterPos → indices of lowercase letters

specialPos → indices of special characters

At the same time, also store the characters themselves.

Step 2: Reverse the characters logically

For letters: first letter index gets last letter character

For specials: first special index gets last special character

No physical reverse needed if you index from the end.

Step 3: Write back into the string

Assign characters back using the stored index positions.

class Solution {
public:
    string reverseLettersThenSpecial(string s) {
        vector<int> letterPos, specialPos;
        vector<char> letters, specials;

        // Step 1: collect positions and characters
        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
            if (s[i] >= 'a' && s[i] <= 'z') {
                letterPos.push_back(i);
                letters.push_back(s[i]);
            } else {
                specialPos.push_back(i);
                specials.push_back(s[i]);
            }
        }

        // Step 2: place letters in reverse order
        for (int i = 0; i < letterPos.size(); i++) {
            s[letterPos[i]] = letters[letters.size() - 1 - i];
        }

        // Step 3: place specials in reverse order
        for (int i = 0; i < specialPos.size(); i++) {
            s[specialPos[i]] = specials[specials.size() - 1 - i];
        }

        return s;
    }
};


Approach 5: 
Step 1: Collect positions

Traverse s once and record:

letterPos: indices where letters occur

specialPos: indices where special characters occur

Step 2: Build a mapping

For letters:

letterPos[i] should get the character from letterPos[k - 1 - i]

For specials:

specialPos[i] should get the character from specialPos[m - 1 - i]

This defines a permutation of indices.

Step 3: Apply the permutation

Create a copy of the string and fill it according to the mapping.

class Solution {
public:
    string reverseLettersThenSpecial(string s) {
        vector<int> letterPos, specialPos;

        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
            if (s[i] >= 'a' && s[i] <= 'z')
                letterPos.push_back(i);
            else
                specialPos.push_back(i);
        }

        string result = s;

        // Apply letter permutation
        for (int i = 0; i < letterPos.size(); i++) {
            result[letterPos[i]] = s[letterPos[letterPos.size() - 1 - i]];
        }

        // Apply special character permutation
        for (int i = 0; i < specialPos.size(); i++) {
            result[specialPos[i]] = s[specialPos[specialPos.size() - 1 - i]];
        }

        return result;
    }
};
